cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.CL, cs.GT, cs.NE 

This paper deals with building a learning-based Scrabble agent using self-play and focuses on finding a better function approximation for the static evaluation function used in Scrabble. The use of evolutionary algorithms and Bayesian Optimization suggests that the paper falls under the category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG). The use of neural networks for function approximation and the raw representation of the Scrabble board as input suggests that the paper also falls under the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL). The exploration of the problem from an Imitation Learning point of view suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of Game Theory (cs.GT) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE).
